Indonesia Stock Movers: Astra Agro, Adaro, Media Nusantara

-- B y   F e m i   A d i
-- 
2011-04-20T09:52:02Z

-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2011-04-20/indonesia-stock-movers-astra-international-media-nusantara.html
Shares of the following companies
had unusual moves in Indonesian trading. Stock symbols are in
parentheses, and prices are as of the noon Jakarta-time break.  The  Jakarta Composite index (JCI)  advanced 31.66 points, or 0.9
percent, to 3,764.31, set for the biggest increase since April 6.  PT Astra Agro Lestari (AALI IJ), the nation’s largest
listed plantation company, advanced 1.8 percent to 22,950 rupiah,
on course for the highest level since March 9. Palm oil futures
rose for a third straight day, adding as much as 1.1 percent to
3,290 ringgit ($1,091) a metric ton in  Kuala Lumpur . Astra Agro
plants only oil palm trees.  PT Adaro Energy (ADRO IJ),  Indonesia ’s second-largest coal
producer, rose 1.1 percent to 2,250 rupiah, set for the biggest
increase since April 6. Shareholders approved a final dividend
of 655.71 billion rupiah ($75.7 million), the company said in a
statement in Jakarta today. The amount will bring the total
dividend payment to 970.77 billion rupiah, or 44 percent of 2010
net income, the highest in the company’s history, Adaro said.  PT Astra International (ASII IJ), Indonesia’s largest
automotive retailer, gained 2.9 percent to 55,200 rupiah. Astra
isn’t aware of any plans to boost the production capacity of
 Toyota Motor Corp. (7203)  vehicles in Indonesia, Yulian Warman, head of
Astra’s public relations division, said by phone today in
Jakarta.  Warman’s comments contradict an earlier confirmation by the
company that Astra planned to increase output of  Toyota vehicles .  Kontan newspaper reported earlier that Astra plans to
increase production of Toyota vehicles to 200,000 units a year
from 150,000 units.  Astra’s current Toyota vehicle production is 100,000 units
a year, Yalman said.  PT Media Nusantara Citra (MNCN IJ), a television company,
jumped 6.3 percent to 850 rupiah, set for the steepest increase
since Feb. 18. Media Nusantara expects revenue this year to rise
65 percent to 8 trillion rupiah ($923 million), bolstered by an
increase in advertisements, Kontan reported, citing President
Director Hary Tanoesoedibjo. Robert Satrya, an investor
relations officer, declined to comment on the report when called
at his office.  To contact the reporter on this story:
